- The PUT /v1/users/{user} endpoint is implemented by App\Http\Controllers\Api\V1\UserController@update.
  - File inspected: app/Http/Controllers/Api/V1/UserController.php.
  - The method signature: update(UsersRequest $request, User $user): UserResource.
  - It calls $this->authorize('update', $user) — so an authorization check occurs and unauthorized access will result in a 403 (AuthorizationException) per Laravel policy behavior.
    - Policy inspected: app/Policies/UserPolicy.php — only the owner (or admin via before()) can update the user.
  - The controller uses a FormRequest UsersRequest for validation.
    - File inspected: app/Http/Requests/UsersRequest.php — rules require 'name' and 'email' (email is validated and unique:unique:users,email,{current_user_id}).
    - Validation failures in Laravel FormRequest return HTTP 422 with a body containing "message" and "errors".
  - If the request contains 'password', the controller hashes it before updating.
  - $user->update(array_filter($request->only(['name','email','password']))) — update returns the updated model and the controller returns new UserResource($user).
- The resource format for the response is defined by App\Http\Resources\User.
  - File inspected: app/Http/Resources/User.php.
  - It returns an array containing the fields:
    - id (numeric)
    - name (string)
